The first virtual operator will be arriving this year in the Czech Republic.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is well developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It probably won't be long before we get there.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTU) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is the most expensive in the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming fees, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS sending from abroad will be cheaper than sending them from home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that you really want to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú), Pavel Dvořák, has already said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be quite difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a marked drop in prices to which classic operators had to respond.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market of Britain, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can be successful.
Besides, there is no need to look for examples too far away.
In February this year we inform you about the premiere of the Virtual Mobilking operator in Poland.
Only after half a year did this operator obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking there is the Penta group that, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, for them to function effectively, they are enough with many fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that however, is often countered with the offer of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Great Britain offers at least half of the cost of competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to bet by a trivial target group.
This operator is specifically addressed to man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it's the operator he likes and who you can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works for this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as that of Poland could bind in our country.
From this, Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav Čepický doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the supply of services it is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be any virtual operators in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it's about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," he said in a telephone conversation for mobile.cz, Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It indirectly ensured that current mobile telephony operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competition arises.
Interest on the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, in order to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And how much sooner, better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile telephony operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings," said the spokesperson of the group, Pavel Kaidl.
So, maybe they're going to brighten up better times.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this point we believe that the situation is suitable for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," he said for mobile.cz, Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specific features of the Czech market relate to other operators.
T-mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with the opinion of O2, adds: "So far we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
And he adds: "On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find some virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table some concrete contract that would be possible to study on such a short horizon."
Vodafone rather directs its attention to the fulfilment of the requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this concerns the sharing of costs and infrastructure.
We consider it to be the biggest customer contribution.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on mobile."
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a fall in prices and thus a decline in profits.
Then why facilitate entry into the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of it is the grip when U:fon came up.
Perhaps the greatest pressure to the ČTÚ was at the time of the U:phone entry by the T-Mobile company.
This is borne out by accessible public information on ČTU websites.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: "Also, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile telephony market was open to a fourth operator.
As regards the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would entail for him and, above all, for his services great requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in trade tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical attitude to this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator to the mobile telephony market would be possible after a convention on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator has been concluded.
To date, no agreement has been closed since the offer of interested potentials was not interesting enough for classic operators", added to our question Kristián Chalupa, from the UOHS Department of External Relations.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that should represent the interests of consumers it is something more than a consideration, besides that they must note that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In other countries where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to lower prices for mobile telephony services"
Of course, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the fall in prices does not fall within the interest of the UOHS.
Indeed the dramatic shock in all this case lies in the dissonant reactions resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in the gas stations as it is clear that it is the work of chance and a tough struggle for competition.
"The Office has not found any signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators therefore have a dominant position and therefore do not have a corresponding rise of responsibility in their market actions.
The tools needed to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators, rather, are missing as well as telecommunications regulators," added Chalupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is obviously an analysis of relevant markets developed by ČTU that telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of Czech operators have a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another view - for a virtual operator to emerge is always necessary agreement with the network administrator.
And the mobile telephony operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for UOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators rise markedly in a similar manner.
Current complaints from stakeholders (insulted by the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that in all negotiations with operators there are many similar impediments.
Loading responsibility in the ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications for which UOHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We have already met with him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law for the extension of ČTU's competition in the field of trade tenders was recently introduced, even though a number of experts promised that the situation would improve.
This should be well known to UOHS representatives, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
Everything's fine, when no one's looking
At the same time, something as well as a pseudovirtual operator continues to work, which already exist in Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that place their own prices on mobile telephony services which, however, only a part are public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Normally only a few elected get the price list of these companies.
Magic is in which the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same by charging a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will later receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile telephony operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as those cited could be discovered, they could talk about infringement in terms of contract conditions that could be translated into the end of collaboration with the given company," answered the question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies cited may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies, they get nothing negligible gains and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of possible problems: "the law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a demeanable so many percent of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card on your phone is not on your behalf so they cannot absolutely have it as a normal customer of operators."
This is exactly what should seem to the ČTÚ minimally strange.
There is also a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile telephony operators surround their eyes in this type of procedure, why block the entrance of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it it should not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that its commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market led to a significant decline in service prices.
At the same time, practically in all countries where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this disruption.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, possibly too saturated, problems with quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases defended operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator emerged and others started to emerge with him.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body all this case happens as if it were a burning nail.
We cannot help but be impressed by the confusion of powers in these cases.
But let us not despair.
If this background information is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile telephony market probably starts moving again.
If one of the operators lets a virtual mobile telephony operator enter, it will be difficult for UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may no longer call more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose Best
Listen to the four presentations of the new Czech official anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the Czech official celebrations presented the new official recording of the hymn Where, my home.
The new hymn was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one with male voice and one with female voice, one with Chorus and another instrumental.
From the song are Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the hymn arrangements are Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio has already said that it intentionally elected for the sole singers with representative young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I have tried with the two and then, too, with the Choir to be fixed in the diction so that the text might be understood well, so that it might have consonance," he said.
The Czech official anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home played for the first time in 1834 on the tables of the State Theatre in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it theirs.
The first stanza of the song following the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became naturally part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
