The MHD in Prague takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, 1 October 2008, it is written in the history of the Prague Transport Company the date on which the first passengers enter the subway, tram and bus with an electronic bonus in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can be purchased at this time by nearly one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy the bonus 30 days, 90 days and the annual (this will be valid as of 1 January 2009) and simultaneously upload it on their chip card at the infocentres and posts of the transport company at the stations of Metro, Muzeum, Męstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The bonuses can be purchased from yesterday on the Internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the Internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget about ticket sales posts at the metro stations, where so far they had to regularly queue to get out a normal ticket.
The bonus is purchased on the internet, and the Opencard card is charged to you in one of the 13 branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is at the disposal of passengers a window with trained staff that helps interested people with the purchase by internet and also with the reloading of the bonus purchased on their card," said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to reload the electronic bonus in the Opencard on the vending machines found in some subway halls.
How are these vending machines?
They are red, they remind us of a ticket pickup machine and travellers will probably have already fixed on them at the stations of the metro of Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Now there are five in the city but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný added.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Just enter the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid bonus will be charged only on it.
The electronic bonuses from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, on the trains and bus lines from the numbers 300 to 499 that mainly use the inhabitants of the towns of Central Bohemia.
"On the trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are auditors equipped with a reader card that will help confirm the validity of the time and the bonus area," explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization that sets the schedules of the collective transport of Prague.
The circus buses have their reader cards mounted in the driver's locker.
When entering it it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also to accompany it with the Opencard at the place intended for it on the side of the Box.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the bonus.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonuses there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal added.
Passengers who do not travel on the circus buses and do not remember when they are finished the validity of the bonus can go to the vending machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown information about the validity of your document.
