Talking Sleepy
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up very often telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk are sleeping.
The first time it happens at best you get scared, but it really doesn't matter.
It is a benign disturbance of the dream that is called dreams.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one of them have been told he talked at night.
This phenomenon may appear very sporadic (once in life for example associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once in months...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines their appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (to sleep) or sleepwalking, but it doesn't have to be like this.
As we have already mentioned, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitement.
Anyway, it's a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
He may speak in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a whisper or otherwise (screaming, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be appropriate to observe the child and consult with a specialist to check whether there is any issue that is generating much anxiety and gives him out in this way.
We have said that it is a benign alteration, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another alteration of the dream that can be treated (e.g. if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress table).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid TV shows or TV series that are either scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children and who find it difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain a certain inner calm.
This will help the child to have a quieter dream.
Once sleepwalks appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything about what has happened.
Useful advice
