The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Héma-Québec has again become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained the public's confidence that had been seriously wavered by the blood scandal contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and public discontent, in February 1994, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would not be repeated.
While Judge Krever was slow to present his relationship, certain provinces then set up a committee that aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee carried out this mission.
As a result of Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, nearly 38% of the people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, says Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
After much effort has been made to improve the safety of blood products and much work during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence " , says before proudly affirming that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94 per cent of the Quebec population subsequently had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that " trust is something extremely fragile " .
Since its inception, on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we attended in Europe the birth of many cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
Then we support one of the main recommendations of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which when we do not know and when a serious illness can emanate from that, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had remained for more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
But some years ago, it has been demonstrated beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleid acid tests that enable donors to detect directly in the blood of the virus, not antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
The nucleid acid tests allowed shortening the period between the moment the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing it and that we will not be able to detect them.
These improvements significantly lowered the risk of contracting AIDS by a blood transfusion.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"That means you will have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone is infected with HIV.
So since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500,000 blood products every year, more than 24 years will pass before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I think it is possible today to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without worries," says the head of the Héma-Québec management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus, such as the West Nile virus, appeared on the island of the Meeting, was transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary pursued before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec should also provide for sufficient supplies.
" Needs increase because the population ages.
Since more aggressive anticancer treatments, patients often need injections of red blood cells or platelets.
Ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors that regroup on average only 3 per cent of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All persons with good health, 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria, however, may donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who propose their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is present, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covered the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But members of this donor network need to be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all, to hold them back and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since the present life is very wild, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate your blood," is distressed Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye balloons and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before they are stored in Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered as biomedical waste is filled with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used for the treatment of severe diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, putting on the bank of our thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood and is expected to take out more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, describing this cord blood intake program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed not to be able to enjoy this " as Héma-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive programme in all hospitals in Quebec.
