Wall Street rescue operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached agreement yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both Congress Chambers.
It foresees in particular: better control by those elected to implement it, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money invested, new provisions to contain the number of houses impounded the lack of payment, as well as a right of control over wages paid to the leaders of the assisted companies.
The American Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, the president of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelossi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a negotiating marathon lasted two days.
" We are making great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
" Everything has been done to cover the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current Wall Street crisis," the Democratic explained.
"It is the fundamental point: if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and disturbances on the daily life of Americans will be immense," declared Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had ended very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect of a further failure in investors' mood.
The last hour they had set was the opening up of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, who have acceded late to the negotiations, were more favourable to the agreement, not forgetting yet to express their dissatisfaction with being forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain provisions to reach the agreement, particularly which would allow the owners to retain their domicile and the salary of the leaders of state-surviving companies.
" When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no need to congratulate them.
But these measures are necessary," he said on American television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, interrogated in another chain to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I would like to see the details, but I hope to vote on it."
"The important points I read [show] that it is something we will have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
He said that the option of not doing anything is not acceptable ".
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers' money the dubious debts, the risk and unsaleable assets of the American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis caused by the outbreak of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risk mortgage credits before extending to other more common forms of credit securities (PCAA) and causing a freezing of liquidity and a disbandment of banks and financial institutions.
It is a group of elected Republicans who had changed the first draft agreement last week.
We believe that we have emerged from stagnation since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to limit the shocks for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision that stipulated that if the government had to take losses for five years with this program, it could impose new fees that would help it recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first part of 250 billion to which an additional 100 billion may be added if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion would have to be confirmed by another vote by Congress.
Instead of their aid, Washington will get shares in the assisted companies that will be worth dividends in case of profits and that will be able to resell when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the possibility of delaying the embargo procedures relating to housing obtained with real estate loans under this plan, as well as setting limits on remuneration and cash compensation paid to the leaders of the companies affected by the crisis.
The architects of the plan would like to see him put to the vote by the House of Representatives today and by the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all its efforts, it is not yet certain that its plan will be approved.
Some people continued to protest yesterday against this project, both from Republicans and Democrats.
Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Commission, told his constituents that "with all evidence, Washington does not want to understand ".
" We have a very serious financial problem.
There are some solutions.
But not the one that consists of making the benefit of taxpayers."
The Democratic representative Brad Sherman, who is an animator of a small group in Congress, presents the problems differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
" Four hundred professors of economics, including three Nobel Prizes, wrote to us to tell us: we ask Congress not to hurry and carefully examine the path to be taken," declared yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, we again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
After an urgent meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group by 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had refused to buy its competitor in bankruptcy since it lost EUR 2 billion ($2.9 billion) during the crisis of risk real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is part of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money, declared yesterday the Dutch Minister of Finance, Wouter Bos.
Instead, we regain a right to vote in the bank and influence.
