The intelligent car mimics the flight of the bee
What would be the best way to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of existing obstacles sensors in nature?
For example, the beekeepers.
In a surprising project presented at the ECATEC in Japan, beekeepers gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic management system of cars like BR23C nature imitator, to which they gave the characteristics of the beeholes, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight each bee creates its own private oval space that actually looks much like our safety protective capsule - explained at the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of PR and development and research.
An important role is played by the eyes composed of bees that are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, the engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
It identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle mimicking the movements of the beech, modifying the direction by rotating the wheels to the necessary extent.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot of the vehicle could not react with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and of the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what makes a bee to dodge other bee.
This process must be carried out in a opening and closing of eyes.
However, unlike bees, the movement cannot turn upwards, downwards or diagonals, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of turning the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bees to dodge other bees, here only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotational movement and acceleration in addition the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and higher its energy density, which means they have a longer life span than that of lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, not even less the storage capacity.
This device in each second should only process some input signals and react as appropriate.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with instinctive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
No memory of gigabytes, no megabytes.
This is the first step to develop the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan calculations, can be incorporated into the models manufactured in series within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding existing obstacles on his way.
