President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelossi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the agreement.
We are pleased with the progress achieved during the night and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy - said Tony Fratto, the spokesperson for the White House.
The program is different from the original proposal of the Bush administration to spend all $700 billion to purchase bad-quality credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after the Congress votes, probably on Monday, from this amount, the Ministry of Finance will buy credit fund securities, poor rating and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president's decision.
This programme will be controlled by a special body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion could be spent after a new Congress decision.
