"Most young Gypsies have not completed secondary education and due to the poor quality of basic education, only a small part can obtain university degrees."
Jaróka further stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, also plays a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights.
Investment in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the Member of the European Parliament, it is necessary to make these issues widely aware among both Roma and non-Gypsies.
For the sooner a Gypsy student starts school, the more possibilities he will have to become an active member of the labour market; through taxes on income and consumption they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and to ensure the abolition of segregation and low-level education," said Livia Járóka.
According to the Euro MP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to speed up school-disaggregation processes immediately, so proper compliance with existing and planned anti-discrimination directives is of fundamental importance.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Roma children the possibility that guarantees democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full-right citizens," Járóka demanded.
The aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organized annually since last year's Berlin meeting in the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities" is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
