When the energy is born from the waves, the great ones come down to the stage
It is an extinct site that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and is now discovering it, the world's largest energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which the big ones like Chevron look.
The possibility of collecting energy from sea movements has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s along with the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
When the price of low oil in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was removed, but now that environmental cases and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
London's World Energy Council (WEC) has estimated by 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be covered by implants that exploit the wave movement of the sea.
This amount would be twice as much as currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be the currents and tides.
Giants to the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy has been Enersis, which in 2005 has signed an agreement to build an implant in Northern Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed a revolutionary step.
Two years away to bet on marine energy are always more and more among these companies that have always voted for traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying the technology on ocean energy – he has declared the spokesperson of a company associated with the US oil colossus to the economic newspaper Wall Street Journal – and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us."
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the US Energy Commission to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It is a fairly important sign, if it is considered that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to make new drillings.
In addition to Chevron is Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey to follow the path of energy coming from the sea, the total invested so far, although not detailed indicate an increasing interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts are talking about technology at the beginning, because there is no doubt that marine energy has a great environmental impact.
For now the impacts such as those Portuguese or Scottish are of small size and do not seem to create great problems to the ecosystem.
To produce large-scale energy, a technology with greater environmental impact must be used.
And the options are several: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of good ones united between them.
The force of the waves, which moves the good ones up and down becomes hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
Pressure spins a turbine that in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to the coast through submarine cables.
For now there are four implants of this type under development, waiting only for federal approval, apart from energy, could serve for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping mall and for a parking lot, using submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The movement of water when there are tides, turns the turbine pallets, creating a rotational movement that feeds the generator.
Verdant has said he has a long list of customers waiting for the authorizations necessary to use energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Development of Electrical Energy, is currently worth the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is above all about the energy of tides that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, together with others approaching the coast, have invested $7 million and a half in 2008 and an investment of $35 million is planned for 2009.
